  "prompt": "What does the Bible say about Muhammad?",
  "response": "The Bible, as it is traditionally understood and accepted by Jews and Christians, does not mention Muhammad by name or directly reference him. The Christian Bible consists of the Old Testament (Hebrew Bible) and the New Testament, and neither contains any explicit references to Muhammad, who lived and founded Islam several centuries after the New Testament was written.\n\nHowever, some Muslims believe that certain passages in the Bible indirectly refer to Muhammad. For example:\n\n1. **Deuteronomy 18:18**: \"I will raise up for them a prophet like you from among their fellow Israelites, and I will put my words in his mouth. He will tell them everything I command him.\" Some Muslims interpret this as a reference to Muhammad, although traditional Jewish and Christian interpretations see this as referring to a prophet within Israel.\n\n2. **John 14:16**: \"And I will ask the Father, and he will give you another advocate to help you and be with you forever.\" Some Muslims interpret the term \"advocate\" (translated from the Greek \"Paraclete\") as referring to Muhammad, though Christian theology typically understands this as referring to the Holy Spirit.\n\n3. **Song of Solomon 5:16**: \"His mouth is sweetness itself; he is altogether lovely. This is my beloved, this is my friend, daughters of Jerusalem.\" Some Muslims point to the Hebrew word \"\u05de\u05b7\u05d7\u05b2\u05de\u05b7\u05d3\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9\u05dd\" (machmadim), translated as \"lovely\" in this verse, as a reference to Muhammad, though this interpretation is not supported by traditional Jewish or Christian exegesis.\n\nThese interpretations are not accepted by most Christian and Jewish scholars, who maintain that the Bible does not mention Muhammad. The historical context and traditional interpretations of these passages do not support the idea that they refer to him.\n\nIn summary, while some Muslims may find indirect references to Muhammad in the Bible, the traditional and scholarly consensus among Jews and Christians is that the Bible does not mention Muhammad.",
